04314nam a22005895i 9780226232454DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20162016ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802262324547 a10.7208/97802262324542doi  a(DE-B1597)523575  a(OCoLC)958654749  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aE767.1b.B87 2017 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a973.9130922231 aBurnidge, Cara Lea, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Peaceful Conquest :bWoodrow Wilson, Religion, and the New World Order /cCara Lea Burnidge. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2016] 4cÂ©2016  a1 online resource (232 p.) :b9 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. From Reconstruction to Regeneration -- t2. Christianization of America in the World -- t3. Blessed Are the Peacemakers -- t4. New World Order -- t5. A Tale of Two Exceptionalisms -- t6. The Crucifixion and Resurrection of Woodrow Wilson -- tConclusion: Formulations of Church and State -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA century after his presidency, Woodrow Wilson remains one of the most compelling and complicated figures ever to occupy the Oval Office. A political outsider, Wilson brought to the presidency a distinctive, strongly held worldview, built on powerful religious traditions that informed his idea of America and its place in the world. With A Peaceful Conquest, Cara Lea Burnidge presents the most detailed analysis yet of how Wilson's religious beliefs affected his vision of American foreign policy, with repercussions that lasted into the Cold War and beyond. Framing Wilson's intellectual development in relationship to the national religious landscape, and paying greater attention to the role of religion than in previous scholarship, Burnidge shows how Wilson's blend of Southern evangelicalism and social Christianity became a central part of how America saw itself in the world, influencing seemingly secular policy decisions in subtle, lasting ways. Ultimately, Burnidge makes a case for Wilson's religiosity as one of the key drivers of the emergence of the public conception of America's unique, indispensable role in international relations. As the presidential election cycle once again raises questions of America's place in the world, A Peaceful Conquest offers a fascinating excavation of its little-known roots.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aChristianity and politicszUnited StatesxProtestant churches. 0aProtestantismxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aProtestantismzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aProtestantismzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aSocial gospelxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package 2014-2016z978311070422808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package 2016z978311068860308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226232454423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226232454.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  a978-3-11-068860-3  UChP eBook-Package 2016b2016  a978-3-11-070422-8  UChP eBook-Package 2014-2016c2014d2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles